On Escalation Ticket # 00419387 the Following Fields have been updated:

On Escalation Ticket # 00419387 the new comment has been added: Robert Zavalczki:

The upgrade will only work from version 5.9.4.1 to newer versions.

However, until then, if our customer still wants to give a try to upgrades, they can add the name 'msiexec' (without the quotes) to the list in the "System Parameters" / "Advanced Scanning Exceptions". Or they can disable the "Advanced Printer and MTP Scanning" feature and try to do the upgrade again.

@WaitingOnEngineer

On Escalation Ticket # 00419387 the Following Fields have been updated:

On Escalation Ticket # 00419387 the new comment has been added: Hello,

The customer has provided feedback regarding the workaround. Unfortunately, the workaround has not resolved the issue of uninstalling and upgrading the client on the tested computer.

We have attached the EPP client logs from when they attempted to reproduce the issue.

On Escalation Ticket # 00419387 the Following Fields have been updated: 
Status has been changed to Awaiting Escalating Engineer.

On Escalation Ticket # 00419387 the new comment has been added: Robert Zavalczki:

The latest logs show that indeed they did what we instructed them to do to enable the upgrades.

However, there is no upgrade command in the logs, in fact they are using the expected EPP agent version from the 5.9.4 product update (6.2.3.1010).

The last upgrade command received from the EPP agent was on August 14th 2024. After that date there are several EPP Agent uninstall commands issued by the EPP server on August-26 and on October-17.

The EPP agent is the latest version. So what is the problem here? @WaitingOnEngineer

[DevOps CommentId:11099256]

On Escalation Ticket # 00419387 the Following Fields have been updated: 
Status has been changed to Awaiting Client.

On Escalation Ticket # 00419387 the new comment has been added: Hello,

Customer provided a new set of logs, while they are upgrading of the client from version 6.2.2.2 to 6.2.3.1. 
The status of this activity is marked as "Upgrade Failed," as shown in the attached screenshot.

On Escalation Ticket # 00419387 the Following Fields have been updated: 
Status has been changed to Awaiting Escalating Engineer.

On Escalation Ticket # 00419387 the new comment has been added: Robert Zavalczki:

In the latest eppclient.log we can only see that an upgrade process was started but the EPP service was not stopped as a result. This means that the upgrade failed at some point. In order for us to determine why it has failed we would need the upgrade log file that can be found here:

"C:WindowsTEMPepp-upgrade.log"

If there is no file there, then maybe they can take a look in the Windows Event Viewer to check if there are any Windows Installer errors. @WaitingOnEngineer

[DevOps CommentId:11165917]

On Escalation Ticket # 00419387 the Following Fields have been updated: 
Status has been changed to Awaiting Client.

On Escalation Ticket # 00419387 the new comment has been added: Hello,

We received information from the customer that the file is located in the temp folder but contains no logs.

Attached is the epp-upgrade log file and screenshot of the MSIInstaller log retrieved from the computer that encountered the upgrade failure.

On Escalation Ticket # 00419387 the Following Fields have been updated: 
Status has been changed to Awaiting Escalating Engineer.

On Escalation Ticket # 00419387 the new comment has been added: Robert Zavalczki:

What about the "C:WindowsTEMPSIEA9A3.tmp" file? Does it still exists on the PC, what is its size? We believe that file is not a valid MSI installer.

If they access this link from a browser:

https://dlp.prodia.co.id/csup/software-win-6.2.3.1010/EPPClientSetup_x86_64.msi

does the browser download a valid MSI installer? If not, then we should have someone from the server team take a look. FYI @WaitingOnEngineer
